reviewText: We LOVE Veggie Tales, own all of them, and are thrilled that our kids enjoy them.  That being said, "It's a Meaningful Life" was cute, but it just didn't have the same spark and Biblical connection that we enjoy from other Veggie Tales DVDs.  The last few have strayed away from the Bible stories and--while they still teach important lessons--we miss that.  I guess it appeals to those who wouldn't consider a Bible-based show, so it has its merits.  Larry and Petunia seem to be the main characters in so many of them lately, but maybe I'm reading too much into it?  The Silly Songs are as clever as they've always been, just amazing.  I actually like the newer songs more than the old school ones as they've been hilariously referencing pop culture.  I think this is worth adding to your collection if you're a VT fan, but our kids never ask for this one; "Little Joe" is our favorite and worth adding to your collection.  The "3-packs" are a wonderful deal, too, and an easy way to build your collection with some awesome Veggie Tales classics. :)
summary: Cute, but nothing like the classics

reviewText: I have been watching Veggie Tales DVD's  longer then I have been a mom. I have yet to find a DVD that I have not enjoyed. The latest animations have been superb and rival larger name companies. The story lines have morals and lessons to learn. You don't have to worry about the wrong language or bad story lines. They are wonderfully family-friendly.The latest DVD we received has been It's a Meaningful Life.  Which takes the same similar story from the Classic "It's a wonderful life". You meet an unhappy Stewart (played by Larry the Cucumber) who is certain his life would be much better if he had not been injured when he was a teenage cucumber. While his life on the outside appears amazing...he is unhappy and thinks he missed out on so much!The part I love most about Veggie Tales is that while they are without a doubt, childrens videos, they have adult humor and are entertaining for the adult viewer as well. It's a Meaningful Life will be a DVD that will become a treasure in our family collection.

reviewText: I love VeggieTales! I really do. As a matter of fact while I type this I am listening to The VeggieTales Incredible Christmas Tree CD that I downloaded (for free!) today from Amazon and AppleBlossom is playing nearby shaking her head back and forth to the music. She loves music and loves to dance and VeggieTales is one of our favorite choices. I hope as she grows we will have a large VeggieTales collection to choose from in both listening to music and watching DVDs. In recent weeks more and more of the older VeggieTales titles have become available on Netflix to view instantly (I'll share my opinions of individual shows soon..) and I just love them!Today I got my hands a copy of the brand new It's a Meaningful Life VeggieTales DVD and it's so much fun! I do believe I want to memorize the brown teddy bear song. ;) VeggieTales really do teach values, and the lesson behind this video is about being content. Although it brings to mind the classic film It's a Wonderful Life, which honestly I've never seen this is my kind of movie and perfect for year round. Easily I can see us watching this one again and again. The what-ifs in life always make you wonder, but learning to be content is such a valuable quality of life and these VeggieTales are great group to help teach your child just exact how to make it work.*Thanks to Christina of LBI for providing a copy for review.*

reviewText: In true VeggieTales style, It's a Meaningful Life takes a familiar, classic Christmas movie and turns it into a fun, whimsical tale for kids.  This tale of being content with your current life and trusting God is one that all kids will need to know.  They need to know that they are truly important to God just the way they are.  Their life is meaningful especially when they are living for God. A servant's heart is a beautiful thing, and fame and fortune aren't always what they are cracked up to be.Our whole family enjoyed this latest VeggieTales episode.  Goodnight Junior was hilarious as it was all too familiar.  Meant to Be is a beautiful song of hope written by Steven Curtis Chapman. Viewers will want to make sure they watch the video as well as the behind the song interview with Steven Curtis Chapman.VeggieTales It's a Meaningful Life is sure to delight viewers young and old.Disclosure: I received a copy of this dvd to help facilitate the writing of this honest review. All opinions are my own.

reviewText: When my son was little, we started watching Veggie Tales soon after they came out.  We liked the stories; they were tasteful and funny, and didn't push the religious angle excessively.  "It's a Meaningful Life" was the first I had seen since the late 90s.The first thing I noticed was the Bible verses right at the beginning.  So the makers have abandoned any interest they might have had in appealing to non-Christians.  That's OK, I guess; they have a market niche, and don't see the point in risking anything.  But it was disappointing.Another change was the animation.  I remember watching a commentary where the makers revealed that they had chosen vegetables for the characters because they were easier to animate.  At the time, computer animation was in its infancy, and Veggie Tales was cutting-edge.  Now, the technology is so cheap that you can produce cartoons like this on a home computer.  It's no trouble at all to add an "arm" codec, where the characters now manipulate objects with invisible limbs, where before, this was kept to a bare minimum.  What's disturbing is that now everyone is wearing clothes, so they don't look like vegetables anymore - they look like Thalidomide victims.  Maybe the change over the years was so gradual as to be unnoticeable to those who watched every movie, but suddenly seeing everyone like that was disconcerting.  What's wrong with keeping the characters as plain, simple vegetables?  Why did they have to spruce it up?The main problem, however, is that the cartoon was unwatchable.  I was expecting an amusing parody of "It's a Wonderful Life," a great classic that nevertheless begs to be parodied.  But the story was so changed as to be unrecognizable, and was so simplistic and cliched that I had to turn it off after the first 5 minutes.  So Veggie Tales, once imaginative and engaging, has descended into formulaic tripe.  Maybe this was inevitable; most mainstream cartoon series end up regurgitating the same jokes over and over until someone puts them out of their misery.But it's still disappointing every time it happens.
